 Orf  ."]}]},{"name":"Iago","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Jacob</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Jacob","meanings":["Biblical name, from Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>. This was borne by perhaps the most important of all the patriarchs in the Book of Genesis. Jacob was the father of twelve sons, who gave their names to the twelve tribes of Israel. He was the son of Isaac and Rebecca and twin brother of Esau. According to the story in Genesis, he was the cunning younger twin, who persuaded his brother Esau to part with his right to his inheritance in exchange for a bowl of soup (‘a mess of pottage’). Later, he tricked his blind and dying father into blessing him in place of Esau. The derivation of the name has been much discussed. It is traditionally explained as being derived from Hebrew <i>akev</i> ‘heel’ and to have meant ‘heel grabber’, because when Jacob was born ‘his hand took hold of Esau's heel’ (Genesis 25:26). This is interpreted later in the Bible as ‘supplanter’ Esau himself remarks, ‘Is he not rightly named Jacob? for he has supplanted me these two times’ (Genesis 27:36). <i>Jacob</i> is especially common as a Jewish given name, although it also became very popular among the Puritans from the 16th century onwards, and has again been widely used since the 1990s.  Compare  James ."]}]},{"name":"ab","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Mabel .   See also  Maeve ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Idwal","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: from <i>iud</i> ‘lord, master’ + <i>(g)wal</i> ‘wall, rampart’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Meurig","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Mauricius</i> via Old Welsh <i>Mouric</i>.  See  <b>Maurice</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Meuric","meanings":["From Latin <i>Mauricius</i> via Old Welsh <i>Mouric</i>.  See  <b>Maurice</b>   ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Iago ab Idwal ap Meurig of Gwynedd King of the Britons was born in 0975, in Aberffraw Castle, Anglesey, Wales, his father, King Idwal ap Meurig of Gwynedd and North Wales, was 30 and his mother, Raggnildr, was 26. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Afandreg ferch Gweir of Aberffraw. He died on 13 October 1039, in his hometown, at the age of 64."},"et":{"0975–13 October 1039":"0975–13. oktoober 1039","0975–1039":"0975–1039","0975–Female":"0975–Surnud","0974–1053":"0974–1053","1014–1075":"1014–1075","1020–1075":"1020–1075","0945–0996":"0945–0996","0950–1016":"0950–1016","1020":"1020","1075":"1075","1053":"1053","0996":"0996","0974":"0974","0975":"0975","Abt 1020":"umbes 1020","0950":"0950","1039":"1039","1016":"1016","13 October 1039":"13. oktoober 1039","1014":"1014","996":"0996","1023":"1023","968":"0968","0945":"0945","Aberffraw Castle, Malltraeth, Anglesey, Wales":"Aberffraw Castle, Anglesey, Wales","Abberffraw Castle, Anglesey, Wales":"Aberffraw Castle, Anglesey, Wales","Caernarfon, Gwynedd, Wales":"Caernarfon, Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom","Aberffraw, Anglesey, Wales":"Aberffraw, Anglesey, Wales","Gwynedd, Wales":"Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom","Dindaethwy, Angelsey, Wales":"Tyndaethwy, Anglesey, Wales"},"fi":{"0975–13 October 1039":"0975–13. lokakuuta 1039","0975–1039":"0975–1039","0975–Female":"0975–Kuollut","0974–1053":"0974–1053","1014–1075":"1014–1075","1020–1075":"1020–1075","0945–0996":"0945–0996","0950–1016":"0950–1016","1020":"1020","1075":"1075","1053":"1053","0996":"0996","0974":"0974","0975":"0975","Abt 1020":"noin 1020","0950":"0950","1039":"1039","1016":"1016","13 Octobe